# Tips

**Leverage automatic responsive behavior**: Figure spacing tokens base on `--content-spacing`, so figures automatically scale for mobile, tablet, and print without explicit media queries. When you adjust document spacing, figures adapt proportionally.

**Choose appropriate isolation**: Default transparent backgrounds work well for most content, creating clean, minimal layouts. Add backgrounds and borders through `--figure-background` and `--figure-border-*` tokens when you need visual separation or want to group related figures.

**Caption alignment matters**: Left-aligned captions (default) work best for multi-paragraph captions and asymmetric layouts. Center-aligned captions suit symmetrical images and formal presentations. Justified alignment works well for scholarly articles with longer captions.

**Maintain label consistency**: Figure labels automatically inherit from semantic label tokens (`--label-font-weight`, `--label-font-style`), ensuring visual consistency with table and equation labels throughout your document.

**Test multi-paragraph captions**: When using backgrounds and borders, verify that multi-paragraph captions clearly belong to the figure. The visual container helps readers understand the caption hierarchy.

**Consider caption width**: The `--figure-caption-max-width` token allows you to constrain caption width independently from figure content width, which can improve readability for wide images with lengthy captions.

**Dark mode integration**: Figure backgrounds and borders automatically adapt to dark themes through semantic token variants. When customizing these tokens, define both light and dark variants for optimal appearance in both modes.

**Accessibility**: Ensure sufficient contrast between caption text color and backgrounds, particularly when using custom `--figure-background` values. Caption colors inherit from semantic caption tokens which provide automatic dark mode support.
